    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "77819598fd4c580e",
      "text": "These other ways of knowing were discredited by the Eurocentric worldview because they violated a central tenet of scientific assumption: if you can't measure it, it isn't real. This conviction was based on the premise – a [[Cartesian Hubris]], really – that our human intellect was the final arbitrator of reality. "
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "24016ea880c00548",
      "text": "Herein lies is a fundamental difference between the Western Ways of Knowing and the Eastern Ways of Knowing. While Western knowing sees the self as the _source_ of understanding, the Eastern knowing sees the self as the _barrier_ to understanding. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cf42e903a3683405",
      "text": "This Eastern knowing, with deep roots back in Hinduism, Buddhism, and Taoism, challenges learners to find deeper understanding beyond the dimensions of intellectual thought – an understanding that flows from a timeless domain of unlimited potential, a domain known variously as Brahman, Nirvana, or the Tao. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "df25cecbdeda9fdb",
      "text": "The Western Ways of Knowing also is inherently individualistic, based on the assumption that we are fundamentally separate from each other and that the universe is simply a collection of distinct parts. This perspective is fundamentally different from the indigenous cultures found around the globe, that share an understanding of the inherent interconnectedness of all things, ourselves included. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "31be3a849b9ede60",
      "text": "Yes, these are simplistic generalities of multidimensional ways of knowing, but as we continue to venture forth on this journey, it may be valuable to recognize that there are profoundly different ways humans have come to make meaning from this magical and profoundly mysterious human experience. "
    },
